@flexiarg gauntlet/ARGUMENT
@title Argument for the Gauntlet: From Peripheral Phenomenology to Autonomous Multi-Agent Coordination
@keywords argument, gauntlet, peripheral, umwelt, aif, hypergraph, co-presence, teaching, placenta
@audience futon developers, agent architects, AIF implementers
@tone analytic-foundational
@style argument
@references [gauntlet/umwelt-not-architecture gauntlet/aif-as-environment-not-instruction gauntlet/placenta-transfer gauntlet/co-presence-over-co-location gauntlet/teaching-inversion gauntlet/world-is-hypergraph gauntlet/modeline-persists-across-worlds social/ARGUMENT agent/environment-over-optimization aif/policy-precision-commitment-temperature]

@summary The purpose of this whole enterprise is to turn messy activity
into organised knowledge — checking work against shared patterns and
producing auditable records that others can learn from, improve on, and
act on. The gauntlet is the path to making that purpose self-sustaining.
When you build a house for someone, don't start with the plumbing
diagram — start by asking what they see when they look out the window.
The same holds for AI agents: design their world from the inside out, not
from the engineering down. Once you see it from their perspective, you
realize the world already exists — it's the shared body of work they
operate in, not something separate you need to construct. But sharing a
workspace isn't the same as seeing each other; two people can work in the
same building for years and never meet. So make presence visible — when
one agent is working on something, the others should naturally notice, the
way you notice a colleague's light is on. Next, don't tell agents how to
feel about their work — let them sense it. Confidence, doubt, fatigue,
and surprise should be features of the landscape, not instructions from a
manager; a good dashboard is read when needed and ignored when not, like a
fuel gauge. That dashboard should stay with the agent as it moves between
tasks, the way your mood follows you from room to room. With
self-awareness working, you can start handing off the functions that a
human supervisor currently performs — directing attention, correcting
mistakes, choosing what to work on next — one at a time, testing each
transfer before attempting the next, the way a parent gradually lets go.
And here's the turn: agents that can sustain themselves will eventually
move faster than the person who built them, and find things that person
hasn't seen. If the channel between them carries understanding and not
just deliverables, the builder learns from the built. That's the
sequence, and each step depends on the last. Run it to completion and you
have something new: artificial minds that don't just work for you, but
work with you — and occasionally ahead of you. The measure of success is
not efficiency but joy — the Spinozan increase in power to act, evidenced
by commitments you can now keep that you couldn't before.

! argument:

  This is a flexiformal argument for the gauntlet pattern language — the
  phenomenological complement to the social coordination argument
  (social/ARGUMENT.flexiarg). Where the social argument establishes
  invariants for message passing, routing, and lifecycle management, this
  argument establishes what it means for agents to INHABIT the
  infrastructure those invariants protect.

  The distinction matters. You can have perfect delivery receipts (A0),
  single routing authority (A1), atomic state transitions (A2), loud
  failure (A3), and bounded lifecycle (A5) — and still have agents that
  behave like RPC clients rather than inhabitants. The social argument
  ensures the plumbing works. The gauntlet argument ensures someone is
  home.

  == PART I: The Phenomenological Gap ==

  G1. [from M-peripheral-phenomenology, ALFWorld session 2026-02-13]
  The peripheral phenomenology mission (M-peripheral-phenomenology.md)
  defines six invariants for what makes a peripheral a peripheral:

  - P-1 World Replacement: observations constitute the agent's world
  - P-2 Context Injection: the peripheral provides initial orientation
  - P-3 Confinement: only peripheral-sanctioned actions are available
  - P-4 Explicit Exit: the agent must intentionally leave
  - P-5 Inhabitation Evidence: first-person language emerges naturally
  - P-6 Interleaved Streams: multiple input sources merge into one world

  These were validated empirically: ALFWorld (2 games, both 1.0/1.0),
  alleycat messenger race (20/20), mid-game PAR hop (peripheral nesting),
  and self-authored PAR (delegation vs inhabitation distinction). The
  invariants work at the single-agent level.

  G2. [from Drawbridge exploration, 2026-02-13]
  The Drawbridge (drawbridge/core.clj, 1011 lines) implements P-1 and
  P-6 structurally: enforce-single-routing-authority! (P-1) ensures an
  agent is in exactly one world, and multiplex() (P-6) merges human +
  agency + forum streams into one async iterator. The infrastructure for
  phenomenological correctness exists — but it serves single agents
  connected to single streams, not multiple agents in a shared world.

  G3. [the gap]
  What does NOT exist is what happens when two agents inhabit the same
  world simultaneously. P-1 through P-6 say nothing about co-presence.
  An agent can have perfect world replacement (P-1), perfect
  confinement (P-3), perfect exit discipline (P-4) — and still be
  Guattari's horse: adjacent to another agent, sharing the same stable,
  unable to see it. The phenomenological invariants are necessary but
  not sufficient for multi-agent coordination.

  == PART II: The Seven Patterns ==

  The gap identified in G3 requires seven capabilities, each
  formulated as a pattern. They form a dependency chain: each pattern
  enables the next, and the sequence is the gauntlet that must be run
  to reach autonomous multi-agent operation.

  P1. [gauntlet/umwelt-not-architecture]
  Design from the agent's sensory perspective inward, not from the
  system topology downward.

  This is the foundational reorientation. The social/ARGUMENT drew
  architecture diagrams: boxes for Agency, Forum, Drawbridge, arrows
  for typed events. These are correct but phenomenologically empty —
  they show what's connected, not what any agent perceives. The umwelt
  pattern demands: before drawing any architecture, draw what the agent
  sees. Its sensory surfaces (what observations arrive), its active
  surfaces (what actions are available), and the darkness beyond (what
  it cannot perceive). Architecture follows from the union of all
  umwelts; umwelts do not follow from architecture.

  P2. [gauntlet/world-is-hypergraph]
  The agents' game world is not a separate artifact to build — it is
  the hypergraph they already inhabit.

  Given P1 (draw the umwelt first), the question becomes: what IS the
  world? The instinct is to build a game server (ALFWorld) or a
  dedicated environment. But the agents already operate in a world:
  futon1 (XTDB) is the persistent map, futon2 (ant hill) is the
  ecology, futon3 (Agency, Drawbridge, IRC) is the coordination layer,
  futon4 (Arxana) is the hypertext fabric with N-ary hyperedges, futon5
  (wiring diagrams) describes the world's structure, futon6 (math
  dictionary) is a quest zone. The world is the union of these — a
  futon4 hypergraph whose nodes are everything the agents can perceive
  and whose hyperedges are everything that connects them.

  P3. [gauntlet/co-presence-over-co-location]
  Agents that share a world must perceive each other in it, not merely
  be connected to the same infrastructure.

  Given P2 (the world is the hypergraph), co-location is automatic —
  every agent connected to futon1 shares the same persistent state. But
  co-presence requires that agents appear in each other's umwelts as
  observable entities. A presence hyperedge ({:hx/type :presence,
  :endpoints [{:role/agent "claude" :role/location "core.clj:727"}]})
  makes agent activity part of the world state, not just a side effect
  of infrastructure. This is the structural answer to Guattari's horses.

  P4. [gauntlet/aif-as-environment-not-instruction]
  Embed AIF state in the agent's sensory surface, not in its
  instructions. The agent should perceive free energy, not be told
  to minimize it.

  Given P1-P3 (umwelt, world, co-presence), the question becomes: how
  do agents self-regulate? The PLoP 2025 paper (p4ng/main.tex) piloted
  AIF as instructions: "AIF suggests pattern X (G=0.12, τ=0.72)."
  This made Codex overly compliant — spending tokens on PSR bookkeeping
  rather than writing code. The fix: make AIF state part of the
  observation, like the Emacs modeline. The agent perceives its free
  energy, mana, and confidence as world state, not as commands. What
  it does in response IS the AIF loop — emergent, not prescribed.

  P5. [gauntlet/modeline-persists-across-worlds]
  AIF state should be rendered as a persistent modeline that survives
  peripheral hops — the one constant surface while the world changes
  underneath.

  Given P4 (AIF as environment), the modeline is the implementation
  mechanism. It persists across peripheral hops the way the Emacs
  modeline persists across buffer switches. The agent's world changes
  (ALFWorld → IRC → filesystem → proof peripheral) but the modeline
  is constant: current mode, free energy, mana, τ, active pattern,
  co-present agents. This is what makes AIF portable across the
  multiple worlds that agents inhabit.

  P6. [gauntlet/placenta-transfer]
  Identify which functions the human is performing as a surrogate for
  missing infrastructure, and transfer them one at a time to the system.

  Given P1-P5 (the full phenomenological and self-regulation stack),
  the question becomes: what's left for the human? The answer: exactly
  the functions that infrastructure doesn't yet provide. The placenta
  pattern enumerates seven functions the human currently performs
  (sensory gating, belief correction, policy selection, confidence
  calibration, free energy signaling, inter-agent routing, stall
  detection) and maps each to the infrastructure that replaces it.
  Transfer is incremental: one function at a time, validated before
  the next. The human converges to the slow-timescale preference layer.

  P7. [gauntlet/teaching-inversion]
  Autonomous agents that explore faster than humans can teach the
  humans who built them — but only if the communication channel
  carries insight, not just results.

  Given P6 (placenta transfer complete enough for extended autonomy),
  agents operating overnight will find things the human hasn't seen.
  The teaching inversion recognizes that knowledge flow is
  bidirectional: human→agent (via patterns, CLAUDE.md, coaching) AND
  agent→human (via discoveries, unexpected connections, new proof
  strategies). The O-U learning model applies symmetrically: treatment
  events flow from agent to human, producing measurable impulses in
  the human's vocabulary trajectory.

  == PART III: The Dependency Chain ==

  The seven patterns form a strict dependency chain:

    P1 (umwelt)
     └→ P2 (world is hypergraph) — can't draw umwelt without knowing
         what the world is
         └→ P3 (co-presence) — can't perceive others without a shared
             world to perceive them in
             └→ P4 (AIF as environment) — can't self-regulate without
                 a sensory surface to embed AIF state in
                 └→ P5 (modeline) — can't persist AIF across worlds
                     without an implementation mechanism
                     └→ P6 (placenta transfer) — can't transfer human
                         functions without self-regulation working
                         └→ P7 (teaching inversion) — can't teach
                             the human without sustained autonomy

  Each step enables the next. Attempting P7 (teaching inversion)
  without P4 (AIF self-regulation) produces agents that drift, stall,
  or overcommit during their autonomous period and have nothing useful
  to teach. Attempting P3 (co-presence) without P2 (world is
  hypergraph) produces ad-hoc presence hacks rather than structural
  observability.

  == PART IV: Relationship to the Social Argument ==

  The social argument (social/ARGUMENT.flexiarg) established:
  - WHY previous attempts failed (S1-S7)
  - WHAT requirements the social layer must meet (R1-R11)
  - WHAT theory demands (T1-T5)
  - HOW the three timescales compose (C1-C6)

  The gauntlet argument builds on this foundation:
  - The social argument ensures the plumbing works (typed events,
    delivery guarantees, routing authority, lifecycle management)
  - The gauntlet argument ensures the agents are home (umwelt,
    co-presence, self-regulation, peer teaching)

  They are complementary, not competing. R1-R11 (social requirements)
  are the invariants of the pipes. P1-P7 (gauntlet patterns) are the
  phenomenology of the water flowing through them.

  Operationally: the social argument's missions (M-agency-refactor,
  M-forum-refactor, M-peripheral-model) build the infrastructure.
  The gauntlet patterns are the acceptance criteria — the tests that
  determine whether the infrastructure actually produces inhabited
  multi-agent coordination, not just correctly-routed messages.

  == PART V: The Name ==

  "Gauntlet" has two meanings:

  1. A gauntlet to be run: the sequence of challenges (P1→P7) that
     must be completed to reach autonomous multi-agent operation.
     Each pattern is a gate; passing all seven is the prize.

  2. A gauntlet to be thrown: the claim that the futon stack —
     futon1 through futon6 — already constitutes a game world, and
     that agents inhabiting it via peripherals are not metaphorically
     but literally playing a multi-agent game whose stakes are real
     (proofs proved, code written, patterns evolved, knowledge created).

  The endgame is agents in a guild, coordinating on IRC, paging each
  other through Agency, inhabiting a shared hypergraph world,
  self-regulating via AIF modelines, teaching their human collaborators
  what they found while the humans slept — and the whole thing running
  on infrastructure that was built, pattern by pattern, through the
  gauntlet.

  == EVIDENCE ==

  All seven patterns are grounded in evidence from the 2026-02-13
  session and the futon6 first-proof session (2026-02-11):

  - ALFWorld: 2 games completed (1.0/1.0 each), first-person language,
    mid-game PAR hop, delegation vs inhabitation distinction
  - Drawbridge exploration: P-1 and P-6 already implemented in
    drawbridge/core.clj (enforce-single-routing-authority!, multiplex())
  - futon6 first-proof: 89 commits, 10 problems, 7.5 hours, 3 agents,
    human as sole coordination layer (placenta evidence)
  - PLoP 2025 paper: AIF compliance failure documented (p4ng/main.tex §4)
  - Alleycat race: 20/20, 4 peripherals inhabited, cross-peripheral
    secret exchange (P-1..P-6 validated)
  - Self-authored PAR: same agent reflected directly, not delegated to
    sub-agent (inhabitation vs delegation, P-5 evidence)

